  "My main point is that we need to move faster on this. Every week we wait, the market moves, and competitors ship features that make our position harder to defend. Speed is not about cutting corners. It is about deciding quickly, testing honestly, and learning from real users before we over invest. When I say faster, I mean shorter cycles, tighter feedback, and fewer meetings that end without a decision. We have the talent and the tools. What we lack is the discipline to commit to a direction and measure the result. So let us agree today that momentum matters, and that a good decision made this week beats a perfect decision made next quarter.",
  "The first checkpoint is product readiness. Before we invite a wider group of testers, the core experience has to work reliably on ordinary hardware and ordinary connections. That means the recording starts when the user expects, the transcript captures the opening words, and the results appear without confusing delays. Product readiness is not a long feature list. It is a small number of things that work every single time. If a first time user records a short session and sees an accurate transcript, we have earned the right to ask for their trust. If they hit an error on the first try, no feature list will save us. So readiness is the gate, and we measure it with real sessions, not demos.",
  "The second checkpoint is user trust. People are sharing their voice and their practice with us, and that is a serious responsibility. Trust comes from privacy, from honesty about what the tool can and cannot do, and from never losing a user's work. If we say the audio stays on the device, it must stay on the device. If the transcript is a draft, we should say it is a draft. Trust is slow to build and fast to lose, so every default we choose should protect the user first. When people believe the tool respects them, they forgive small rough edges. When they suspect it does not, even a polished product feels hollow.",
  "The third checkpoint is operational evidence. We do not ship on optimism. We ship on measurements that we can defend. That means we watch real latency, real accuracy, and real error rates on the actual devices our users have. Evidence means committed logs and reproducible tests, not a confident summary in a meeting. If a number looks too good, we check it twice, and we look for the clip that breaks it. Operational evidence is what turns a hopeful plan into a decision we can stand behind. It is also what tells us honestly when we are not ready, which is just as valuable as knowing when we are.",
